</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>a</sup>Department of Medicine, Johns Hopkins University, School of Medicine, Baltimore, MD, USA</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>b</sup>Department of Mental Health, Johns Hopkins University, Bloomberg School of Public Health, Baltimore, MD, USA</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>c</sup>Baltimore Polytechnic Institute, Baltimore, MD, USA</div>
<div id="A4">
<sup>d</sup>Institute of Public Health, National Yang-Ming University, Taipei, Taiwan</div>
<div id="A5">
<sup>e</sup>National Institute on Aging, Intramural Research program, Laboratory of Behavioral Neuroscience, Baltimore, MD, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline">Correspondence to: Sevil Yasar, MD, PhD, Johns Hopkins University, School of Medicine, Department of Medicine, Division of Geriatric Medicine &amp; Gerontology, 5200 Eastern Ave, MFL Center Tower, #727, Baltimore, MD 21224, USA. Tel.: 410 550 2668; Fax: 410 550 2513; <span>syasar1@jhmi.edu</span>.</p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC7293768  NIHMSID: NIHMS1596430  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32280103/" class="usa-link">32280103</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.3233/JAD-200118" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">J Alzheimers Dis</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Background:</h3>
<p id="P1">There is emerging evidence about possible involvement of the renin-angiotensin system (RAS) in the pathogenesis of Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and decline of cognitive function. However, little is known about associations with brain biomarkers.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Objective:</h3>
<p id="P2">Our study aimed to examine associations between blood ACE-1 and ANG II levels and brain MRI based volumes in non-demented participants, and whether these associations were mediated by blood pressure.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods:</h3>
<p id="P3">This cross-sectional study was conducted in 34 older participants from the Baltimore Experience Corps Trial (BECT) Brain Health Sub-study (BHS). Blood ANGII and ACE-1 levels were measured by ELISA and brain MRI volumes were generated using FreeSurfer 6.0. Multiple linear regression analysis, adjusting for intracranial volume and confounders, was used to determine associations between log transformed ANGII and ACE-1 levels and MRI volumes (mm<sup>3</sup>).</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results:</h3>
<p id="P4">Participants were predominantly female (76%), African-American (94%), with mean age of 66.9 and education of 14.4 years. In the fully adjusted model we observed significant inverse associations between log ANGII levels and total grey matter (β=Angiotensin II associated with smaller hippocampus 14,935.50, ±7,444.83, <em>p</em> = 0.05), total hippocampus (β=−129.97, ±105.27, <em>p</em> = 0.03), rostral middle frontal (β = −1580.40, ±584.74, <em>p</em> = 0.02), and supramarginal parietal (β = −978.90, ±365.54, <em>p</em> = 0.02) volumes. There were no associations between ANGII levels and total white matter or entorhinal cortex volumes, or ACE-1 levels and any brain volumes.</p></section><section id="S5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion:</h3>
<p id="P5">We observed that increased blood ANGII levels were associated with lower total grey matter, hippocampal, rostral middle frontal, and supramarginal parietal volumes, which are associated with cognitive domains that decline in preclinical AD.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Angiotensin II, angiotensin converting enzyme-1, cohort study, MRI</p></section></section><section id="S6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p id="P6">There is increasing evidence in recent years for the involvement of the renin angiotensin system (RAS) in Alzheimer’s disease (AD) pathogenesis [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>]. The RAS generates bioactive angiotensin peptides with a wide range of biological activities involved not only in blood pressure regulation, but possibly also in the pathogenesis of AD, either independently or in combination with BP control [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>]. These peptides likely have effects on vascular function and modulation of amyloid and tau metabolism in AD [<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>]. Previous autopsy studies have shown that people with AD have increased angiotensin converting enzyme 1 (ACE-1) activity resulting in increased conversion of angiotensin I (ANGI) to II (ANGII) [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>, <a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>], which is a potent vasoconstrictor. Similarly, decreased angiotensin converting enzyme 2 (ACE-2) activity was found to decrease conversion of ANGII to the vasodilator angiotensin 1–7 [<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>]. All these changes resulted in increased levels of ANGII causing increased activation of angiotensin type-1 receptor (AGT1 R), which is associated with accumulation of amyloid-β (Aβ) and tau, and also with decreased acetylcholine release, all of which contribute to AD pathogenesis [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>]. Few studies have been done evaluating role of RAS peptides in AD process in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and/or blood. One study measured blood ACE-1 levels and found lower levels and greater reduction in levels in participants with AD when compared to normal controls [<a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>]. While another study evaluated ACE-1 activity and levels in postmortem CSF and found lower levels, but not change in activity, in participants with AD when compared to normal controls [<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>].</p>
<p id="P7">We have previously shown in cognitively normal Brain Health Sub-study (BHS) participants that higher ACE-1 levels predicted worse processing speed and working memory after 1-year follow-up [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. There are currently no studies available evaluating associations between blood levels of ANGII and or ACE-1 and brain MRI biomarkers. Thus, in our study we have explored associations between blood ANGII and ACE-1 levels and MRI based volumetric measures in the same population from our prior study [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>] 1) associated with AD related brain atrophy: total grey and white matter, hippocampus, entorhinal cortex and 2) associated with cognitive domains [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>] identified in prior work (i.e., speed and working memory) [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]: rostral middle frontal gyrus, superior frontal gyrus, supramarginal parietal gyrus, and inferior parietal gyrus. We further explored whether these associations were potentially mediated by blood pressure.</p></section><section id="S7"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">METHODS AND MATERIALS</h2>
<section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Participants</h3>
<p id="P8">The Brain Health Study (BHS) [<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>, <a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>], a nested study within the Baltimore Experience Corps Trial (BECT). The BECT was a sex-stratified, randomized, controlled effectiveness trial to evaluate the health benefits for older adults participating in a high-intensity volunteer service program versus a waitlist control group, and details were previously published on the recruitment and design of BECT [<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>, <a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>]. The nested BHS simultaneously recruited eligible participants prior to randomization to evaluate the benefits of the program on their brain and biological health. From January 2006 to December 2009, 702 eligible participants were randomized for the 2-year trial to either intervention. During BECT randomization, 123 participants were invited to enroll in the nested BHS who were free of dementia at baseline. Criteria for enrollment in the BHS have been described previously [<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>, <a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>]. Baseline and follow-up evaluations BECT included medical history, neurological, psychiatric, and neuropsychological examinations and laboratory studies. Participants also enrolled in the BHS underwent structural and functional brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) at baseline and two subsequent annual follow-up visits 12 and 24 months after baseline. Fifty-six participants attending follow-up visits [<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>] were recruited to our pilot study to collect blood in order to explore associations between ACE-1 and ANGII levels and cognition and volumetric brain imaging. Inclusion criteria for the study included consent to a fasting blood draw, free of brain disease (tumor, neurodegenerative diseases, infection, cerebrovascular disease, psychiatric disease, and delirium), inflammatory disease (autoimmune), end stage renal and liver disease, or cancer, and no use of angiotensin converting enzyme-1 inhibitor (ACE-I) or angiotensin 1 receptor blockers (ATRB) in previous 3 months. Of the 56 participants, 22 participants were missing either MRI (e.g., had no MRI imaging or had poor image quality) or blood assay measures (e.g., undetectable measures), resulting in a final analytic sample of 34 participants where both blood and MRI measures were available from the same visit. The study was approved by the institutional IRB of the Johns Hopkins University and participants provided written informed consent.</p>
<p id="P9">Demographic information (age, gender, race, years of education) was assessed using questionnaires; medical history was based on self-report history of myocardial infarction, stroke, transient ischemic attack, heart failure, hypertension, and diabetes mellitus. Additionally, anthropometric measures included height and weight, BP readings, cognitive, physical, and health data were collected concurrently with blood.</p></section><section id="S9"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Blood ACE-1 and ANGII assay</h3>
<section id="S10"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Blood collection and storage</h4>
<p id="P10">Blood draw procedures and processing followed established protocols using standard venipuncture procedures after an 8-h fast for the proposed study. Peripheral venous blood samples for ACE-1 levels were obtained (5 ml), allowed to clot for 20 min and were centrifuged at 800 rpm for 10 min at 22°C. After centrifugation, serum was aliquoted in 1 ml vials and were taken to the Johns Hopkins University (JHU) Institute for Clinical and Translational Research (ICTR) Core Laboratory, where it was stored at −80° C until assayed. For the ANGII levels, blood samples were obtained (5 ml) from the participants and were immediately centrifuged 800 rpm for 10 min at 22°C. After centrifugation, the clear EDTA plasma layer (approximately 1 ml) was collected and taken to the JHUICTR Core Laboratory, where it was stored at −80° C until assayed. Blood assays were performed using standardized procedures in JHU ICTR Core Laboratory. ACE-1 and ANGII were assayed at the same time with duplicate samples and controls to ensure low interassay variance.</p></section><section id="S11"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Immunoassays</h4>
<p id="P11">A commercially available sandwich ELISA (R&amp;D systems) was used according to the manufacturer’s guidelines to measure ACE-1 levels in serum. ACE-1 concentrations were determined by interpolation from the standard curve determined for each plate from the known. The concentration of ACE-1 is expressed in ng/ml. The interassay coefficient of variance for ACE-1 measurements was 3%. The assay sensitivity was 0.05 ng/ml. The concentrations of ANGII were measured by enzyme immunoassay using plates coated with ANGII monoclonal antibody and a detection antibody labeled with acetylcholinesterase, and ANGII inhibitor cocktail and phenyl cartridges for sample preparation and extraction following the manufacturer’s protocol (Cayman Chemical). The concentration of ANGII is expressed in pg/ml. The interassay coefficient of variance for ANGII measurements was 6.2%. The assay sensitivity was 2.0 pg/ml. ACE-1 and ANGII measurements were normalized using log-transformations.</p></section></section><section id="S12"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Outcome measures</h3>
<section id="S13"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">MRI volumetric measures</h4>
<p id="P12">Tl-weighted imaging was done on 3.0T scanner (Phillips, Best, Netherlands) using the magnetization prepared rapid-acquisition gradient echo (MPRAGE) protocol with TR = 8ms, TE = 3.6ms, matrix size = 256×256, slices 200 and the field of view (FOV) 256×256 mm. Brain volumetric measures are reported in mm<sup>3</sup> and include total cortical gray matter, white matter, hippocampal, and entorhinal volumes, which are all affected by AD. Additionally rostral middle frontal gyrus, superior frontal gyrus, supramarginal parietal gyrus, and inferior parietal gyrus were also included since all are associated with processing speed and working memory [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>], which we have previously found to be associated with ACE-1 levels [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>].</p>
<p id="P13">Volumes were generated using FreeSurfer 6.0 [<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>, <a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>], adjusted for intracranial volume, and regional volumes were summed to produce bi-hemispheric measures.</p></section><section id="S14"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Blood pressure</h4>
<p id="P14">At each study visit, BP was measured by trained staff according to standard protocols. BP was measured while the participant was sitting in an upright position with legs uncrossed and feet flat on the floor for approximately 5 min. Three blood pressure readings, with 30-s intervals between each measurement, were obtained on the right arm using a mercury sphygmomanometer with an appropriatesized occluding cuff and were averaged for data analysis. Measures of systolic blood pressure (SBP) and diastolic blood pressure (DBP) were used in analyses.</p></section></section><section id="S15"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical analysis</h3>
<p id="P15">Participants baseline characteristics were summarized using frequencies with percentages or means with standard deviations (SD). Participants undergoing blood analysis were compared to those without blood analysis using analysis of variance test of equal means for continuous measures and Fisher’s exact test for categorical measures.</p>
<p id="P16">Multiple linear regression models were used for evaluating associations between log(ACE-1) and log(ANGII) levels, and MRI volumetric measures. In the first model, linear regression analyses were used and adjusted for study randomization (intervention versus control); in the second model, analyses were further adjusted for potential confounding variables (age, sex, education, number of chronic diseases, SBP and DBP, body mass index (BMI), and Geriatric Depression Scale (GDS). The number of chronic diseases variable was a sum of any self-reported medical conditions including hypertension, diabetes mellitus, stroke, coronary artery disease, and chronic heart failure. We did not adjust for race since a majority (94%) of participants were African American. Due to concern of over-adjustment, we have pre-adjusted for intracranial volume (ICV) for volumetric outcomes, thus ICV was not included in the final models. In exploratory analyses, we additionally evaluated potential associations between log(ACE-1) and log(ANGII) and blood pressure measures, and blood pressures and MRI volumetric measures. These exploratory analyses also evaluated whether associations between blood levels of ACE-1 and ANGII and MRI volumetric measures may be mediated by blood pressure.</p>
<p id="P17">The <em>a priori</em> significance level was set at <em>p</em> &lt; 0.05. STATA 15.1 was used for all analyses (Stata Corp, College Station, TX).</p></section></section><section id="S16"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">RESULTS</h2>
<section id="S17"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Participants</h3>
<p id="P18">There were 34 participants with a mean age of 66.9 (6.4) years, 26 (76%) were females, and 32 (94%) were African Americans with mean of 14.4 (±2.6) years of education (<a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>). Mean SBP was 137.8 (±17.2) and DBP 76.5 (±10.6) mm Hg while BMI was 31.7 (±6.0) kg/m<sup>2</sup>, and 21 (64%) participants had history of hypertension. Participants with blood assays were less likely to report hypertension and diabetes than participants not assayed, but they did not differ significantly in other baseline demographic and health related characteristics (<a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>). The ICV-adjusted mean volumes for total grey matter were 504,100 (±45,428) mm<sup>3</sup>, total white matter 393,396 (±50,780) mm<sup>3</sup>, total hippocampus 6,744 (±704) mm<sup>3</sup>, 504,100 (±45,428) mm<sup>3</sup>, entorhinal cortex 3,505 (±727) mm<sup>3</sup>, rostral middle frontal gyrus 22,341 (±3,423) mm<sup>3</sup>, superior frontal gyrus 33,454 (±3,487) mm<sup>3</sup>, inferior parietal gyrus 19,819 (±2,377) mm<sup>3</sup>, and supramarginal gyrus 16,042 (±2,294) mm<sup>3</sup>.</p>
