</div></section></section><section id="S18"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Cross-sectional associations</h3>
<section id="S19"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Blood levels of ACE-1 and ANGII</h4>
<p id="P19">Using Pearson correlation there was a significant correlation between ACE-1 and ANGII levels (<em>r</em> = 0.36; <em>p</em> = 0.048) (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Supplementary Figure 1</a>).</p></section><section id="S20"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Blood levels of ACE-1 and ANGII, and MRI volumetric measures</h4>
<p id="P20">In the fully adjusted models, there were no significant associations between log(ACE-I) levels and MRI volumetric measures (mm<sup>3</sup>) (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>). However, we observed significant inverse associations between log(ANGII) levels and total grey matter (β = −14,935.50, ±7,444.83, <em>p</em> = 0.05), total hippocampus (β = −129.97, ±105.27, <em>p</em> = 0.03), rostral middle frontal (β = −1580.40, ±584.74, <em>p</em> = 0.02), and supramarginal parietal (β = −978.90, ±365.54, <em>p</em> = 0.02) volumes (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>). There were no significant associations between ANGII levels and total white matter or entorhinal cortex volumes.</p>
