</div></section></section></section></section><section id="S23"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">DISCUSSION</h2>
<p id="P23">In our study, we evaluated associations between blood levels of ACE-1 and ANGII and MRI volumetric measures in a subset of 34 cognitively normal community dwelling participants with high vascular risk factor burden in the Brain Health Study (BHS). We found that higher baseline ANGII levels were associated with lower total grey matter, hippocampal, rostral middle frontal, and supramarginal parietal volumes, all associated with memory and executive function and this was independent of blood pressure control. Our findings are in line with a previous study showing that variants of AGTR1 gene, which encodes AGTR1 the main receptor for ANGII, were associated with accelerated hippocampal volume loss over a 4-year period [<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>]. However, in contrast to another longitudinal study, which showed that presence of ACE I/I genotype associated with lower ACE-1 blood levels, was associated with smaller hippocampus and higher risk for AD over a 6-year period in women [<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>], we did not find similar associations between ACE-1 levels and hippocampal volume. This could be explained by the cross-sectional nature of our study and the small sample size. Our findings are especially noteworthy since we not only evaluated associations of well-known brain biomarkers involved in AD pathogenesis, but also regional brain volumes, that may better pinpoint the clinical significance and potential mechanisms by which ACE-1 and ANGII may also accelerate age-related cognitive decline.</p>
<p id="P24">Our study capitalizes on recent advances in RAS neurobiology and adds new information to fill the gap in understanding the role of RAS in cognitive aging as a potential precursor to dementia. The RAS likely plays an important role in cognitive function [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>, <a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>]. This was supported by our other recent study in the BHS, where we found that higher ACE-1 levels predicted worse cognition one year later [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. We hypothesized that cognitive changes are preceded by brain volume changes associated in processing speed and/or working memory. There are only a few studies evaluating blood levels of ACE-1 and ANGII in relation to brain volumes in part due to the assay requirement of specifically pre-treated blood. One cross-sectional study showed no association between cerebrospinal fluid and blood ACE-1 levels and cortical atrophy [<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>]. Our study is the first to evaluate associations between both ACE-1 and ANGII blood levels and detailed MRI volumetric measures in a non-demented older adult population. Additionally, we took into account the potential mediating role of blood pressure [<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>] in the effect of ACE and ANGII on brain volumes.</p>
<p id="P25">Our findings lend support to findings from epidemiological studies showing that antihypertensive medications acting via the RAS, such as ACE-I and ATRB, are protective against cognitive decline [<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>–<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>]. It, however, needs to be noted that results of numerous randomized clinical trials evaluating the effect of ACE-I and/or ATRB blockers on risk of cognitive impairment and function in hypertensive patients have been mixed [<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a>–<a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a>], perhaps due to the fact that dementia was a secondary outcome thus studies may have been underpowered.</p>
<p id="P26">Our findings however also raise some questions regarding our previous findings of no associations between ANGII and cognitive function [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. One possible explanation could be that structural changes occur before cognitive changes [<a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31</a>] and longitudinal follow-up longer than one year is needed to suggest associations. Other possible explanation is the fact that only ACE-1 and ANGII levels of the complex RAS were measured, thus lacking evaluation of other peptides potentially involved in the complex mechanisms.</p>
<p id="P27">There is very little literature about associations between white matter volume and RAS. In our study we found no association between white matter volume and ANGII or ACE-1 levels. A recent study of healthy older adults showed that theM268T polymorphism of angiotensinogen, the precursor of ANGI which is then converted to ANGII, was associated with increased ANGII and alteration of microstructure of white matter. In this study white matter was measured using T2-weighted fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery (FLAIR) and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) [<a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a>]; therefore, the T1-weighted images used in our study may have not been sensitive enough to detect associations.</p>
<p id="P28">There are a number of strengths of this study. First, we explored associations in a well-characterized, sociodemographically at risk cohort of highly functioning, community-dwelling, older participants free of cognitive impairment at baseline with detailed medical history, MRI imaging, and cognitive testing. Second, the study examined participants who were free from cognitive impairment at baseline, however, at risk for future cognitive impairment due to various sociodemographic factors. Third, participants of this study were the same participants from our prior study when we evaluated associations between ACE-1 and ANGII levels and cognitive functions, thus it enables us to draw more mechanistic conclusions. Fourth, we were able to explore the possible role of blood pressure levels in order to explore one aspect of possible mechanisms. Having said that, the small sample size did not allow us to stratify participants by presence of absence of hypertension, which would be important to clearly evaluate the role of blood pressure in these associations.</p>
<p id="P29">There are limitations of this study. First, the sample size of our posthoc study was small, which may have limited the power to detect associations while at the same time low power can also increase the possibility of false positive results. The significant associations we observed are particularly meaningful considering the small sample size. Second, since this study involved mainly older African American women, findings have yet to be replicated in other and larger populations. Nonetheless, this under-represented group has numerous medical and demographic risk factors that place them at elevated risk for dementia. Third, only ACE-1 and ANGII levels of the RAS were measured, thus the entirety of the complex RAS mechanisms may not be captured. Fourth, the MRI volumetric and BP analyses were cross-sectional, and findings should be replicated in future longitudinal studies to better establish the temporal relationship between RAS markers and brain outcomes. Fifth, we did not have measurements of hippocampal subfield available, however future work can examine hippocampal subregions to determine whether RAS biomarkers differentially affect memory subsystems.</p>
<p id="P30">In summary, this study indicates that ANGII levels were associated with smaller total grey, hippocampal, rostral middle frontal, and supramarginal parietal volumes, and this effect may be independent of blood pressure. Like with every study in order to confirm our hypothesis we first need to replicate our findings, both cross-sectionally and longitudionally, in a larger cohort, which is more representative of the general population, while using more sensitive MRI imaging to measure small vessel disease. Our results, however, also warrant further research with additional blood and CSF markers of the RAS, in a larger cohort including participants with both normal and impaired cognition, and following them for a longer period in order to evaluate possible effects of RAS to improve identification of pharmacologic targets for preventive interventions to slow cognitive decline and delay the progression to dementia.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
